In[11]:
import pandas as pd

data_review = pd.Series(data['Reviews'])

def remove_numeric(series):
    result=[x for x in series if x.isnumeric()==False]
    return result

result_series = remove_numeric(data_review)

print("\nSeries without Numeric Values:")
print(result_series)

# Define custom labels (one less than the number of bins)
labels = ['0-1K', '1K-10K', '10K-20K', '20K-50K', '50K-100K', '100K-250K', '250K-500K', '500K-1M', '1M-10M', '10M-100M', '100M+']

# Bin the 'Reviews' column and assign custom labels
new_data['Reviews Category'] = pd.cut(new_data['Reviews'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=True)

import re

def split_numeric_alphabetic(s):
    match = re.match(r"([0-9.]+)([A-Za-z]+)", s)
    if match:
        numeric_part, alphabetic_part = match.groups()
        return float(numeric_part), alphabetic_part
    else:
        return None

def convert_to_numeric(value):
    if 'M' in value:
        return value
    elif 'k' in value:
        numeric_part, alphabetic_part = split_numeric_alphabetic(value)
        numeric_part=round(numeric_part/1000,1)
        value=str(numeric_part)+'M'
        return value
    else:
        return value

# Get the counts of each category

# Create a new Series with the top 6 categories and the "Others" category

  • Followed by Game (10.8%), Tools(8.1%), Business(4.1%), Medical(3.9%).
  • Top 6 category itself contributiong ~49.7% of all applications on the platform.
  • While Rest of the categories consists of 50.3% of the applications on the platform.

Inferences:

  • Family category leads the Play Store: The Family category comprises the largest share of apps on the platform, contributing to 18.7% of all applications. This suggests a strong presence of family-oriented apps catering to various age groups.

  • Concentration in Top Categories: The top 6 categories, including Family, Game, Tools, Business, and Medical, collectively account for approximately half (49.7%) of all applications available on the Play Store. This concentration indicates a significant focus on specific app genres by developers and reflects user preferences and demands.

This diversity underscores the wide array of app types available beyond the prominent categories, catering to niche interests and specific user needs.

Overall, these insights highlight the dynamic nature of the Play Store ecosystem, characterized by a mix of popular categories driving app adoption and a diverse range of specialized applications serving various user interests.
